body:
I was asked to solve this formula for $R_2$: $$\frac{1}{R} = \frac{1}{R_1} + \frac{1}{R_2} + \frac{1}{R_3}$$ So I did the following: \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{R_2} &= \frac{1}{R} - \frac{1}{R_1}-\frac{1}{R_3} \\[8pt]
 &= \frac{R_1R_3-RR_3-RR_1}{RR_1R_3}
\end{align*}
Then I took the inverse of both sides to get:
$$R_2 = \frac{RR_1R_3}{R_1R_3-RR_3-RR_1}$$ It seems to be correct but I don't know. So is it?
